create.!doc: Creates a new object with the specified prototype object and properties.

keys.!doc: Returns an array of a given object's own enumerable properties, in the same order as that provided by a for-in loop (the difference being that a for-in loop enumerates properties in the prototype chain as well).

seal.!doc: Seals an object, preventing new properties from being added to it and marking all existing properties as non-configurable. Values of present properties can still be changed as long as they are writable.

isSealed.!doc: Determine if an object is sealed.

freeze.!doc: Freezes an object: that is, prevents new properties from being added to it; prevents existing properties from being removed; and prevents existing properties, or their enumerability, configurability, or writability, from being changed. In essence the object is made effectively immutable. The method returns the object being frozen.

isFrozen.!doc: Determine if an object is frozen.

preventExtensions.!doc: Prevents new properties from ever being added to an object.

isExtensible.!doc: The Object.isExtensible() method determines if an object is extensible (whether it can have new properties added to it).

assign.!doc: The Object.assign() method is used to copy the values of all enumerable own properties from one or more source objects to a target object. It will return the target object.

is.!doc: The Object.is() method determines whether two values are the same value.

toString.!doc: Returns a string representing the object.

toLocaleString.!doc: Returns a string representing the object. This method is meant to be overriden by derived objects for locale-specific purposes.

valueOf.!doc: Returns the primitive value of the specified object

hasOwnProperty.!doc: Returns a boolean indicating whether the object has the specified property.

propertyIsEnumerable.!doc: Returns a Boolean indicating whether the specified property is enumerable.

isPrototypeOf.!doc: Tests for an object in another object's prototype chain.

apply.!doc: Calls a function with a given this value and arguments provided as an array (or an array like object).

call.!doc: Calls a function with a given this value and arguments provided individually.

bind.!doc: Creates a new function that, when called, has its this keyword set to the provided value, with a given sequence of arguments preceding any provided when the new function was called.

Function.!doc: Every function in JavaScript is actually a Function object.

isArray.!doc: Returns true if an object is an array, false if it is not.

from.!type: fn(arrayLike: ?, mapFn?: fn(elt: ?, i: number) -> ?, thisArg?: ?) -> [!0.<i>]
from.!doc: The Array.from() method creates a new Array instance from an array-like or iterable object.

of.!doc: The Array.of() method creates a new Array instance with a variable number of arguments, regardless of number or type of the arguments.

length.!doc: An unsigned, 32-bit integer that specifies the number of elements in an array.

concat.!doc: Returns a new array comprised of this array joined with other array(s) and/or value(s).

join.!doc: Joins all elements of an array into a string.

splice.!doc: Changes the content of an array, adding new elements while removing old elements.

pop.!doc: Removes the last element from an array and returns that element.

push.!doc: Mutates an array by appending the given elements and returning the new length of the array.

shift.!doc: Removes the first element from an array and returns that element. This method changes the length of the array.

unshift.!doc: Adds one or more elements to the beginning of an array and returns the new length of the array.

slice.!doc: Returns a shallow copy of a portion of an array.

reverse.!doc: Reverses an array in place.  The first array element becomes the last and the last becomes the first.

sort.!doc: Sorts the elements of an array in place and returns the array.

indexOf.!doc: Returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present.

lastIndexOf.!doc: Returns the last index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present. The array is searched backwards, starting at fromIndex.

every.!type: fn(test: fn(elt: ?, i: number, array: +Array) -> bool, context?: ?) -> bool
every.!doc: Tests whether all elements in the array pass the test implemented by the provided function.

some.!type: fn(test: fn(elt: ?, i: number, array: +Array) -> bool, context?: ?) -> bool
some.!doc: Tests whether some element in the array passes the test implemented by the provided function.

filter.!type: fn(test: fn(elt: ?, i: number, array: +Array) -> bool, context?: ?) -> !this
filter.!doc: Creates a new array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function.

forEach.!type: fn(f: fn(elt: ?, i: number, array: +Array), context?: ?)
forEach.!doc: Executes a provided function once per array element.

map.!type: fn(f: fn(elt: ?, i: number, array: +Array) -> ?, context?: ?) -> [!0.!ret]
map.!doc: Creates a new array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in this array.

reduce.!type: fn(combine: fn(sum: ?, elt: ?, i: number, array: +Array) -> ?, init?: ?) -> !0.!ret
reduce.!doc: Apply a function against an accumulator and each value of the array (from left-to-right) as to reduce it to a single value.

reduceRight.!type: fn(combine: fn(sum: ?, elt: ?, i: number, array: +Array) -> ?, init?: ?) -> !0.!ret
reduceRight.!doc: Apply a function simultaneously against two values of the array (from right-to-left) as to reduce it to a single value.

copyWithin.!type: fn(target: number, start: number, end?: number) -> !this
copyWithin.!doc: The copyWithin() method copies the sequence of array elements within the array to the position starting at target. The copy is taken from the index positions of the second and third arguments start and end.

entries.!doc: The entries() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the key/value pairs for each index in the array.

fill.!doc: The fill() method fills all the elements of an array from a start index to an end index with a static value.

find.!type: fn(callback: fn(element: ?, index: number, array: [?]) -> bool, thisArg?: ?) -> !this.<i>
find.!doc: The find() method returns a value in the array, if an element in the array satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise undefined is returned.

findIndex.!type: fn(callback: fn(element: ?, index: number, array: [?]), thisArg?: ?) -> number
findIndex.!doc: The findIndex() method returns an index in the array, if an element in the array satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise -1 is returned.

keys.!doc: The keys() method returns a new Array Iterator that contains the keys for each index in the array.

values.!doc: The values() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the values for each index in the array.

:Symbol.iterator.!doc: Returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the values for each index in the array.

includes.!doc: Determines whether an array includes a certain element, returning true or false as appropriate.

Array.!doc: The JavaScript Array global object is a constructor for arrays, which are high-level, list-like objects.

fromCharCode.!doc: Returns a string created by using the specified sequence of Unicode values.

fromCodePoint.!doc: The static String.fromCodePoint() method returns a string created by using the specified sequence of code points.

raw.!doc: The static String.raw() method is a tag function of template strings, used to get the raw string form of template strings.

length.!doc: Represents the length of a string.

charAt.!doc: Returns the specified character from a string.

charCodeAt.!doc: Returns the numeric Unicode value of the character at the given index (except for unicode codepoints > 0x10000).

indexOf.!doc:
Returns the index within the calling String object of the first occurrence of the specified value, starting the search at fromIndex,
returns -1 if the value is not found.

lastIndexOf.!doc: Returns the index within the calling String object of the last occurrence of the specified value, or -1 if not found. The calling string is searched backward, starting at fromIndex.

substring.!doc: Returns a subset of a string between one index and another, or through the end of the string.

substr.!doc: Returns the characters in a string beginning at the specified location through the specified number of characters.

slice.!doc: Extracts a section of a string and returns a new string.

trim.!doc: Removes whitespace from both ends of the string.

toUpperCase.!doc: Returns the calling string value converted to uppercase.

toLowerCase.!doc: Returns the calling string value converted to lowercase.

toLocaleUpperCase.!doc: Returns the calling string value converted to upper case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.

toLocaleLowerCase.!doc: Returns the calling string value converted to lower case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.

split.!doc: Splits a String object into an array of strings by separating the string into substrings.

concat.!doc: Combines the text of two or more strings and returns a new string.

localeCompare.!doc: Returns a number indicating whether a reference string comes before or after or is the same as the given string in sort order.

match.!doc: Used to retrieve the matches when matching a string against a regular expression.

replace.!doc: Returns a new string with some or all matches of a pattern replaced by a replacement.  The pattern can be a string or a RegExp, and the replacement can be a string or a function to be called for each match.

search.!doc: Executes the search for a match between a regular expression and this String object.

codePointAt.!doc: The codePointAt() method returns a non-negative integer that is the UTF-16 encoded code point value.

endsWith.!doc: The endsWith() method determines whether a string ends with the characters of another string, returning true or false as appropriate.

includes.!doc: The includes() method determines whether one string may be found within another string, returning true or false as appropriate.

normalize.!doc: The normalize() method returns the Unicode Normalization Form of a given string (if the value isn't a string, it will be converted to one first).

repeat.!doc: The repeat() method constructs and returns a new string which contains the specified number of copies of the string on which it was called, concatenated together.

startsWith.!doc: The startsWith() method determines whether a string begins with the characters of another string, returning true or false as appropriate.

:Symbol.iterator.!doc: Returns a new Iterator object that iterates over the code points of a String value, returning each code point as a String value.

String.!doc: The String global object is a constructor for strings, or a sequence of characters.

MAX_VALUE.!doc: The maximum numeric value representable in JavaScript.

MIN_VALUE.!doc: The smallest positive numeric value representable in JavaScript.

POSITIVE_INFINITY.!doc: A value representing the positive Infinity value.

NEGATIVE_INFINITY.!doc: A value representing the negative Infinity value.

toString.!doc: Returns a string representing the specified Number object

toFixed.!doc: Formats a number using fixed-point notation

toExponential.!doc: Returns a string representing the Number object in exponential notation

toPrecision.!doc: The toPrecision() method returns a string representing the number to the specified precision.

EPSILON.!doc: The Number.EPSILON property represents the difference between one and the smallest value greater than one that can be represented as a Number.

MAX_SAFE_INTEGER.!doc: The Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER constant represents the maximum safe integer in JavaScript (253 - 1).

MIN_SAFE_INTEGER.!doc: The Number.MIN_SAFE_INTEGER constant represents the minimum safe integer in JavaScript (-(253 - 1)).

isFinite.!doc: The Number.isFinite() method determines whether the passed value is finite.

isInteger.!doc: The Number.isInteger() method determines whether the passed value is an integer.

isNaN.!doc: The Number.isNaN() method determines whether the passed value is NaN. More robust version of the original global isNaN().

isSafeInteger.!doc: The Number.isSafeInteger() method determines whether the provided value is a number that is a safe integer. A safe integer is an integer that

parseFloat.!doc: The Number.parseFloat() method parses a string argument and returns a floating point number.

parseInt.!doc: The Number.parseInt() method parses a string argument and returns an integer of the specified radix or base.

Number.!doc: The Number JavaScript object is a wrapper object allowing you to work with numerical values. A Number object is created using the Number() constructor.

Boolean.!doc: The Boolean object is an object wrapper for a boolean value.

exec.!doc: Executes a search for a match in a specified string. Returns a result array, or null.

test.!doc: Executes the search for a match between a regular expression and a specified string. Returns true or false.

global.!doc: Creates a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern.

ignoreCase.!doc: Creates a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern.

multiline.!doc: Reflects whether or not to search in strings across multiple lines.

source.!doc: A read-only property that contains the text of the pattern, excluding the forward slashes.

lastIndex.!doc: A read/write integer property that specifies the index at which to start the next match.

flags.!doc: The flags property returns a string consisting of the flags of the current regular expression object.

sticky.!doc: The sticky property reflects whether or not the search is sticky (searches in strings only from the index indicated by the lastIndex property of this regular expression). sticky is a read-only property of an individual regular expression object.

unicode.!doc: The 'u' flag enables various Unicode-related features.

RegExp.!doc: Creates a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern.

parse.!doc: Parses a string representation of a date, and returns the number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC.

UTC.!type: fn(year: number, month: number, date: number, hour?: number, min?: number, sec?: number, ms?: number) -> number
UTC.!doc: Accepts the same parameters as the longest form of the constructor, and returns the number of milliseconds in a Date object since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00, universal time.

now.!doc: Returns the number of milliseconds elapsed since 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC.

toUTCString.!doc: Converts a date to a string, using the universal time convention.

toISOString.!doc: JavaScript provides a direct way to convert a date object into a string in ISO format, the ISO 8601 Extended Format.

toDateString.!doc: Returns the date portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

toTimeString.!doc: Returns the time portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

toLocaleDateString.!doc: Converts a date to a string, returning the "date" portion using the operating system's locale's conventions.

toLocaleTimeString.!doc: Converts a date to a string, returning the "time" portion using the current locale's conventions.

getTime.!doc: Returns the numeric value corresponding to the time for the specified date according to universal time.

getFullYear.!doc: Returns the year of the specified date according to local time.

getYear.!doc: Returns the year in the specified date according to local time.

getMonth.!doc: Returns the month in the specified date according to local time.

getUTCMonth.!doc: Returns the month of the specified date according to universal time.

getDate.!doc: Returns the day of the month for the specified date according to local time.

getUTCDate.!doc: Returns the day (date) of the month in the specified date according to universal time.

getDay.!doc: Returns the day of the week for the specified date according to local time.

getUTCDay.!doc: Returns the day of the week in the specified date according to universal time.

getHours.!doc: Returns the hour for the specified date according to local time.

getUTCHours.!doc: Returns the hours in the specified date according to universal time.

getMinutes.!doc: Returns the minutes in the specified date according to local time.

getUTCMinutes.!doc: Creates JavaScript Date instances which let you work with dates and times.

getSeconds.!doc: Returns the seconds in the specified date according to local time.

getUTCSeconds.!doc: Returns the seconds in the specified date according to universal time.

getMilliseconds.!doc: Returns the milliseconds in the specified date according to local time.

getUTCMilliseconds.!doc: Returns the milliseconds in the specified date according to universal time.

getTimezoneOffset.!doc: Returns the time-zone offset from UTC, in minutes, for the current locale.

setTime.!doc: Sets the Date object to the time represented by a number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC.

setFullYear.!doc: Sets the full year for a specified date according to local time.

setUTCFullYear.!doc: Sets the full year for a specified date according to universal time.

setMonth.!doc: Set the month for a specified date according to local time.

setUTCMonth.!doc: Sets the month for a specified date according to universal time.

setDate.!doc: Sets the day of the month for a specified date according to local time.

setUTCDate.!doc: Sets the day of the month for a specified date according to universal time.

setHours.!doc: Sets the hours for a specified date according to local time, and returns the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC until the time represented by the updated Date instance.

setUTCHours.!doc: Sets the hour for a specified date according to universal time.

setMinutes.!doc: Sets the minutes for a specified date according to local time.

setUTCMinutes.!doc: Sets the minutes for a specified date according to universal time.

setSeconds.!doc: Sets the seconds for a specified date according to local time.

setUTCSeconds.!doc: Sets the seconds for a specified date according to universal time.

setMilliseconds.!doc: Sets the milliseconds for a specified date according to local time.

setUTCMilliseconds.!doc: Sets the milliseconds for a specified date according to universal time.

toJSON.!doc: Returns a string (using toISOString()) representing the Date object's value.

Date.!doc: Creates JavaScript Date instances which let you work with dates and times.

parseInt.!doc: Parses a string argument and returns an integer of the specified radix or base.

parseFloat.!doc: Parses a string argument and returns a floating point number.

isNaN.!doc: Determines whether a value is NaN or not. Be careful, this function is broken. You may be interested in ECMAScript 6 Number.isNaN.

isFinite.!doc: Determines whether the passed value is a finite number.

encodeURI.!doc: Encodes a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) by replacing each instance of certain characters by one, two, three, or four escape sequences representing the UTF-8 encoding of the character (will only be four escape sequences for characters composed of two "surrogate" characters).

encodeURIComponent.!doc: Encodes a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) component by replacing each instance of certain characters by one, two, three, or four escape sequences representing the UTF-8 encoding of the character (will only be four escape sequences for characters composed of two "surrogate" characters).

decodeURI.!doc: Decodes a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) previously created by encodeURI or by a similar routine.

decodeURIComponent.!doc: Decodes a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) component previously created by encodeURIComponent or by a similar routine.

E.!doc: The base of natural logarithms, e, approximately 2.718.

SQRT1_2.!doc: The square root of 1/2; equivalently, 1 over the square root of 2, approximately 0.707.

PI.!doc: The ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter, approximately 3.14159.

abs.!doc: Returns the absolute value of a number.

cos.!doc: Returns the cosine of a number.

sin.!doc: Returns the sine of a number.

tan.!doc: Returns the tangent of a number.

acos.!doc: Returns the arccosine (in radians) of a number.

asin.!doc: Returns the arcsine (in radians) of a number.

atan.!doc: Returns the arctangent (in radians) of a number.

atan2.!doc: Returns the arctangent of the quotient of its arguments.

ceil.!doc: Returns the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number.

floor.!doc: Returns the largest integer less than or equal to a number.

round.!doc: Returns the value of a number rounded to the nearest integer.

exp.!doc: Returns Ex, where x is the argument, and E is Euler's constant, the base of the natural logarithms.

log.!doc: Returns the natural logarithm (base E) of a number.

sqrt.!doc: Returns the square root of a number.

pow.!doc: Returns base to the exponent power, that is, baseexponent.

max.!doc: Returns the largest of zero or more numbers.

min.!doc: Returns the smallest of zero or more numbers.

random.!doc: Returns a floating-point, pseudo-random number in the range [0, 1) that is, from 0 (inclusive) up to but not including 1 (exclusive), which you can then scale to your desired range.

acosh.!doc: The Math.acosh() function returns the hyperbolic arc-cosine of a number.

asinh.!doc: The Math.asinh() function returns the hyperbolic arcsine of a number.

atanh.!doc: The Math.atanh() function returns the hyperbolic arctangent of a number.

cbrt.!doc: The Math.cbrt() function returns the cube root of a number.

clz32.!doc: The Math.clz32() function returns the number of leading zero bits in the 32-bit binary representation of a number.

cosh.!doc: The Math.cosh() function returns the hyperbolic cosine of a number, that can be expressed using the constant e:

expm1.!doc: The Math.expm1() function returns ex - 1, where x is the argument, and e the base of the natural logarithms.

fround.!doc: The Math.fround() function returns the nearest single precision float representation of a number.

hypot.!doc: The Math.hypot() function returns the square root of the sum of squares of its arguments.

imul.!doc: The Math.imul() function returns the result of the C-like 32-bit multiplication of the two parameters.

log10.!doc: The Math.log10() function returns the base 10 logarithm of a number.

log1p.!doc: The Math.log1p() function returns the natural logarithm (base e) of 1 + a number.

log2.!doc: The Math.log2() function returns the base 2 logarithm of a number.

sign.!doc: The Math.sign() function returns the sign of a number, indicating whether the number is positive, negative or zero.

sinh.!doc: The Math.sinh() function returns the hyperbolic sine of a number, that can be expressed using the constant e:

tanh.!doc: The Math.tanh() function returns the hyperbolic tangent of a number.

trunc.!doc: The Math.trunc() function returns the integral part of a number by removing any fractional digits. It does not round any numbers. The function can be expressed with the floor() and ceil() function:

Math.!doc: A built-in object that has properties and methods for mathematical constants and functions.

parse.!type: fn(json: string, reviver?: fn(key: string, value: ?) -> ?) -> ?
parse.!doc: Parse a string as JSON, optionally transforming the value produced by parsing.

stringify.!type: fn(value: ?, replacer?: fn(key: string, value: ?) -> ?, space?: string|number) -> string
stringify.!doc: Convert a value to JSON, optionally replacing values if a replacer function is specified, or optionally including only the specified properties if a replacer array is specified.

JSON.!doc: JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a data-interchange format.  It closely resembles a subset of JavaScript syntax, although it is not a strict subset. (See JSON in the JavaScript Reference for full details.)  It is useful when writing any kind of JavaScript-based application, including websites and browser extensions.  For example, you might store user information in JSON format in a cookie, or you might store extension preferences in JSON in a string-valued browser preference.

Map.!doc: The Map object is a simple key/value map. Any value (both objects and primitive values) may be used as either a key or a value.

clear.!doc: The clear() method removes all elements from a Map object.

delete.!doc: The delete() method removes the specified element from a Map object.

entries.!doc: The entries() method returns a new Iterator object that contains the [key, value] pairs for each element in the Map object in insertion order.

forEach.!doc: The forEach() method executes a provided function once per each key/value pair in the Map object, in insertion order.

get.!doc: The get() method returns a specified element from a Map object.

has.!doc: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified key exists or not.

keys.!doc: The keys() method returns a new Iterator object that contains the keys for each element in the Map object in insertion order.

set.!doc: The set() method adds a new element with a specified key and value to a Map object.

size.!doc: The size accessor property returns the number of elements in a Map object.

values.!doc: The values() method returns a new Iterator object that contains the values for each element in the Map object in insertion order.

:Symbol.iterator.!doc: Returns a new Iterator object that contains the [key, value] pairs for each element in the Map object in insertion order.

Set.!doc: The Set object lets you store unique values of any type, whether primitive values or object references.

add.!doc: The add() method appends a new element with a specified value to the end of a Set object.

clear.!doc: The clear() method removes all elements from a Set object.

delete.!doc: The delete() method removes the specified element from a Set object.

entries.!doc: The entries() method returns a new Iterator object that contains an array of [value, value] for each element in the Set object, in insertion order. For Set objects there is no key like in Map objects. However, to keep the API similar to the Map object, each entry has the same value for its key and value here, so that an array [value, value] is returned.

forEach.!doc: The forEach() method executes a provided function once per each value in the Set object, in insertion order.

has.!doc: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified value exists in a Set object or not.

keys.!doc: The values() method returns a new Iterator object that contains the values for each element in the Set object in insertion order.

size.!doc: The size accessor property returns the number of elements in a Set object.

values.!doc: The values() method returns a new Iterator object that contains the values for each element in the Set object in insertion order.

:Symbol.iterator.!doc: Returns a new Iterator object that contains the values for each element in the Set object in insertion order.

Symbol.!doc: A symbol is a unique and immutable data type and may be used as an identifier for object properties. The symbol object is an implicit object wrapper for the symbol primitive data type.

for.!doc: The Symbol.for(key) method searches for existing symbols in a runtime-wide symbol registry with the given key and returns it if found. Otherwise a new symbol gets created in the global symbol registry with this key.

keyFor.!doc: The Symbol.keyFor(sym) method retrieves a shared symbol key from the global symbol registry for the given symbol.

WeakMap.!doc: The WeakMap object is a collection of key/value pairs in which the keys are objects and the values can be arbitrary values.

delete.!doc: The delete() method removes the specified element from a WeakMap object.

get.!doc: The get() method returns a specified element from a WeakMap object.

has.!doc: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified key exists in the WeakMap object or not.

set.!doc: The set() method adds a new element with a specified key and value to a WeakMap object.

WeakSet.!doc: The WeakSet object lets you store weakly held objects in a collection.

add.!doc: The add() method appends a new object to the end of a WeakSet object.

delete.!doc: The delete() method removes the specified element from a WeakSet object.

has.!doc: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an object exists in a WeakSet or not.
